{"award_age":61.0,"bio_image":"full\/05dcf698d5f4eb90cb93f01ce7631414fa008109.jpg","category":"Chemistry","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1911-06-25T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1980-02-02T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/d\/dd\/William_Howard_Stein.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/William_H._Stein","mini_bio":"<p><b>William Howard Stein<\/b> (June 25, 1911 \u2013 February 2, 1980) was an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemist\" title=\"Biochemist\">biochemist<\/a>.<\/p><p>Stein was born and died in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City<\/a>. He was the son of Beatrice Cecilla (Borg), a children's rights activist, and Fred Michael Stein, a banker.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/William_H._Stein#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was educated at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Phillips_Exeter_Academy\" title=\"Phillips Exeter Academy\">Phillips Exeter Academy<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Columbia_University\" title=\"Columbia University\">Columbia University<\/a>. He was a subsequently a researcher under <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Max_Bergmann\" title=\"Max Bergmann\">Max Bergmann<\/a> at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rockefeller_University\" title=\"Rockefeller University\">Rockefeller University<\/a>, where much of his most important work was done.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobel_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/William_H._Stein#cite_note-Nobel-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Stein won a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> in 1972 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Christian_Boehmer_Anfinsen\" title=\"Christian Boehmer Anfinsen\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Christian Boehmer Anfinsen<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stanford_Moore\" title=\"Stanford Moore\">Stanford Moore<\/a>, for their work on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ribonuclease\" title=\"Ribonuclease\">ribonuclease<\/a> and for their contribution to the understanding of the connection between <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemical_structure\" title=\"Chemical structure\">chemical structure<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Catalysis\" title=\"Catalysis\">catalytic activity<\/a> of the ribonuclease molecule.<\/p><p>In 1958 he and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stanford_Moore\" title=\"Stanford Moore\">Stanford Moore<\/a> developed the first automated <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Amino_acid\" title=\"Amino acid\">amino acid<\/a> analyzer, which facilitated the determination of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Protein_sequence\" title=\"Protein sequence\" class=\"mw-redirect\">protein sequences<\/a>. Stein remained at Rockefeller for his entire career, and held visiting professorships at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Washington_University_at_St._Louis\" title=\"Washington University at St. Louis\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Washington University at St. Louis<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Haverford_College\" title=\"Haverford College\">Haverford College<\/a>, the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobel_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/William_H._Stein#cite_note-Nobel-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"William H. Stein","place_of_birth":null,"place_of_death":null,"text":"William H. Stein , Chemistry, 1972","year":1972.0}